  "title": "Data-driven prediction of polymer surface adhesion using high-throughput MD and hybrid network models",
  "experiments_summary": "The study employed coarse-grained molecular dynamics (MD) simulations to generate a dataset of polymer-surface binding free energies. Surfaces (20×20 lattices) and polymer sequences (40-bead chains) with varying compositions (0.1-0.9 fractions) were designed using 1D and 2D Ising Monte Carlo models, generating 92 unique surfaces and 92 unique polymer sequences. Umbrella sampling MD simulations (~0.85 million simulations total, 58 windows per system) were performed using GROMACS 2021.4 with PLUMED 2.8, with the polymer center-of-mass distance from surface (z-axis) as the collective variable. Systems were simulated for 4,000,000 steps (20 ns) at 300K using Langevin thermostat. Potential of mean force (PMF) profiles were computed using weighted histogram analysis method (WHAM), yielding 8464 binding free energies. A hybrid deep learning architecture was developed combining: (1) 2D CNN for surface encoding (two convolutional blocks with 32 and 64 filters, max-pooling), (2) single-layer GRU (64 hidden units) for polymer sequence encoding, and (3) multi-head attention mechanism (2 heads, key dimension 64) where polymer features serve as queries and surface features as keys/values. The model includes feedforward layers (250, 140, 100 units) with dropout (0.2), trained using Nadam optimizer (learning rate 10^-4) with MAE loss. Symmetry-based data augmentation was applied using canonical forms to handle rotational and flip invariances. Model performance was benchmarked against baseline DNN and alternative polymer encoders (1D CNN, BiGRU, LSTM, BiLSTM)."
